<subSubSection id="C33ADDAFFF8CFFE0FF46F945FC138D98" lastPageId="65" lastPageNumber="66" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FF8CFF9EFF46F945FAEF883A" blockId="63.[151,1436,1698,2011]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
Diagnosis: Similar in appearance to 
<taxonomicName id="4C20F5A7FF8CFF9EFD92F944FDE989A7" box="[579,633,1699,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Dasysyrphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lotus">
<emphasis id="B9545236FF8CFF9EFD92F944FDE989A7" box="[579,633,1699,1723]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">lotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="131B92A1FF8CFF9EFD5DF945FCAA89A6" box="[652,826,1698,1722]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="46.[151,250,1509,1532]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,337,1488]" captionTargetId="figure-316@46.[151,1436,337,1488]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 10. Dasysyrphus lotus: A: female (CNCD 26389) dorsal habitus; B: female (CNCD 26389) lateral habitus; C: wing base (CNCD 26397); D: lateral view of male (JSS 18303) genitalia. Dorsal and lateral habitus scale bar = 1mm, genitalia and wing scale bar = 500µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5266311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5266311/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Figs 10A &amp; B</figureCitation>
), with maculae on tergites 3&amp;4 oblique, uniform in thickness, meeting medially and not crossing the abdominal margin (
<figureCitation id="131B92A1FF8CFF9EFC79F921FBC089C2" box="[936,1104,1734,1758]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,494,1535]" captionTargetId="figure-339@64.[151,1436,486,1536]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 16. Dasysyrphus richardi: A: female (USNM ENT 00258072) dorsal habitus; B: wing base (USNM ENT 00258072); C: female (USNM ENT 00258072) lateral habitus. Dorsal and lateral habitus scale bar = 1mm, wing scale bar = 500µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265895" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265895/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Figs 16A &amp; C</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C20F5A7FF8CFF9EFBB4F921FAC989C2" authorityName="Locke &amp; Skevington" authorityYear="2013" box="[1125,1369,1734,1758]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Dasysyrphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="richardi">
<emphasis id="B9545236FF8CFF9EFBB4F921FAC989C2" box="[1125,1369,1734,1758]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Dasysyrphus richardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a dark vitta separating the gena from the face (
<figureCitation id="131B92A1FF8CFF9EFD75F90DFCDD881E" box="[676,845,1770,1794]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,494,1535]" captionTargetId="figure-339@64.[151,1436,486,1536]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 16. Dasysyrphus richardi: A: female (USNM ENT 00258072) dorsal habitus; B: wing base (USNM ENT 00258072); C: female (USNM ENT 00258072) lateral habitus. Dorsal and lateral habitus scale bar = 1mm, wing scale bar = 500µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265895" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265895/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Figs 16A &amp; C</figureCitation>
) and the wing extensively bare basally (
<figureCitation id="131B92A1FF8CFF9EFAF4F90DFA1E881E" box="[1317,1422,1770,1794]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,494,1535]" captionTargetId="figure-339@64.[151,1436,486,1536]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 16. Dasysyrphus richardi: A: female (USNM ENT 00258072) dorsal habitus; B: wing base (USNM ENT 00258072); C: female (USNM ENT 00258072) lateral habitus. Dorsal and lateral habitus scale bar = 1mm, wing scale bar = 500µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265895" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265895/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Fig. 16B</figureCitation>
), where as 
<taxonomicName id="4C20F5A7FF8CFF9EFED1F8E9FEA6883A" box="[256,310,1806,1830]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Dasysyrphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lotus">
<emphasis id="B9545236FF8CFF9EFED1F8E9FEA6883A" box="[256,310,1806,1830]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">lotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is continuously light from face to gena (
<figureCitation id="131B92A1FF8CFF9EFD2CF8E9FCF1883A" box="[765,865,1806,1830]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="46.[151,250,1509,1532]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,337,1488]" captionTargetId="figure-316@46.[151,1436,337,1488]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 10. Dasysyrphus lotus: A: female (CNCD 26389) dorsal habitus; B: female (CNCD 26389) lateral habitus; C: wing base (CNCD 26397); D: lateral view of male (JSS 18303) genitalia. Dorsal and lateral habitus scale bar = 1mm, genitalia and wing scale bar = 500µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5266311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5266311/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
) and the wing is more microtrichose (
<figureCitation id="131B92A1FF8CFF9EFADDF8E9FAE3883A" box="[1292,1395,1806,1830]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="46.[151,250,1509,1532]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,337,1488]" captionTargetId="figure-316@46.[151,1436,337,1488]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 10. Dasysyrphus lotus: A: female (CNCD 26389) dorsal habitus; B: female (CNCD 26389) lateral habitus; C: wing base (CNCD 26397); D: lateral view of male (JSS 18303) genitalia. Dorsal and lateral habitus scale bar = 1mm, genitalia and wing scale bar = 500µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5266311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5266311/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FF8CFF9EFF16F8D5FEC28856" blockId="63.[151,1436,1698,2011]" box="[199,338,1842,1866]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Description:</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FF8CFF9EFF16F8B1FC898872" blockId="63.[151,1436,1698,2011]" box="[199,793,1878,1902]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
Body Length: 7.2–8.0mm; Wing Length: 
<quantity id="4CD823C1FF8CFF9EFD48F8B1FC898872" box="[665,793,1878,1902]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.35" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="7.2" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="7.35" valueMax="7.5" valueMin="7.2">7.2–7.5mm</quantity>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FF8CFFE1FF16F89DFBF98FC8" blockId="63.[151,1436,1698,2011]" lastBlockId="64.[151,1436,151,433]" lastPageId="64" lastPageNumber="65" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
Head: Frons dark with light pollenose fascia (in female it is ½ the length between the antennae and ocelli and is continuous, sometimes notched medially) and dark pile; face light with dark vitta medially, that is &lt;¼ the width of the face, not reaching antennal socket, face with dark pile; gena light with light pile and sometimes interspersed with dark pile, separated from face by dark vitta (
<figureCitation id="131B92A1FFF3FFE1FD1CFF70FCE48FB3" box="[717,884,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,494,1535]" captionTargetId="figure-339@64.[151,1436,486,1536]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 16. Dasysyrphus richardi: A: female (USNM ENT 00258072) dorsal habitus; B: wing base (USNM ENT 00258072); C: female (USNM ENT 00258072) lateral habitus. Dorsal and lateral habitus scale bar = 1mm, wing scale bar = 500µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265895" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265895/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Figs 16A &amp; C</figureCitation>
); occiput dark, covered in light pollen, pile light with some dark pile dorsally; scape and pedicel dark, flagellomere dark, lighter at base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FFF3FFE1FF16FF38FCA58EAD" blockId="64.[151,1436,151,433]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
Thorax: Scutum dark, may appear shiny or metallic, with two faint pollenose vittae medially, extending just past the transverse suture, pile light; scutellum light with darker lateral edges, light pile with some dark pile posteriorly; wing cells br and bm entirely bare, cell c bare at base and along Sc, r 
<subScript id="17A48C61FFF3FFE1FBF1FED0FBB88E59" attach="left" box="[1056,1064,311,325]" fontSize="6" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">1</subScript>
bare at base and cup bare at base and along vein CuP and posterior edge, r 
<subScript id="17A48C61FFF3FFE1FDB4FEB9FDED8E70" attach="left" box="[613,637,350,364]" fontSize="6" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">2+3</subScript>
, r 
<subScript id="17A48C61FFF3FFE1FD44FEB9FD3D8E70" attach="left" box="[661,685,350,364]" fontSize="6" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">4+5</subScript>
, dm, cua 
<subScript id="17A48C61FFF3FFE1FCC4FEB9FC8D8E70" attach="left" box="[789,797,350,364]" fontSize="6" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">1</subScript>
and anal lobe with bare areas at base (
<figureCitation id="131B92A1FFF3FFE1FB02FEA8FAAA8E7B" box="[1235,1338,335,359]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,494,1535]" captionTargetId="figure-339@64.[151,1436,486,1536]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 16. Dasysyrphus richardi: A: female (USNM ENT 00258072) dorsal habitus; B: wing base (USNM ENT 00258072); C: female (USNM ENT 00258072) lateral habitus. Dorsal and lateral habitus scale bar = 1mm, wing scale bar = 500µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265895" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265895/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 16B</figureCitation>
); haltere light; pro- and mesofemur ⅓–½ dark basally, ½–⅔ light apically, metafemur ⅔–¾ dark basally, ¼–⅓ light apically, tibiae light, metatibia slightly darkened medially, tarsi light.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF5FDEACFFF3FFE1FF46F9F2FAC98956" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265895" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5265895" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265895/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" startId="64.[151,250,1557,1580]" targetBox="[151,1434,494,1535]" targetPageId="64">
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FFF3FFE1FF46F9F2FAC98956" blockId="64.[151,1436,1557,1610]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis id="B9545236FFF3FFE1FF46F9F2FE8F8930" bold="true" box="[151,287,1557,1580]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">FIGURE 16.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C20F5A7FFF3FFE1FEF5F9F1FE6F8930" authorityName="Locke &amp; Skevington" authorityYear="2013" box="[292,511,1558,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Dasysyrphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="richardi">
<emphasis id="B9545236FFF3FFE1FEF5F9F1FE6F8930" box="[292,511,1558,1580]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Dasysyrphus richardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: A: female (USNM ENT 00258072) dorsal habitus; B: wing base (USNM ENT 00258072); C: female (USNM ENT 00258072) lateral habitus. Dorsal and lateral habitus scale bar = 1mm, wing scale bar = 500µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FFF3FFE1FF16F990FAD189CB" blockId="64.[151,1436,1654,2003]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
Abdomen: Maculae on tergite 2 large, oval to triangular, slightly narrowed on medial end, ⅓–&lt;½ width of tergite, maculae on tergites 3&amp;4 are straight and oblique, meeting medially, maculae do not reach abdominal margin and are uniform in thickness (
<figureCitation id="131B92A1FFF3FFE1FDEBF958FD4C89CB" box="[570,732,1727,1751]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,494,1535]" captionTargetId="figure-339@64.[151,1436,486,1536]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 16. Dasysyrphus richardi: A: female (USNM ENT 00258072) dorsal habitus; B: wing base (USNM ENT 00258072); C: female (USNM ENT 00258072) lateral habitus. Dorsal and lateral habitus scale bar = 1mm, wing scale bar = 500µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265895" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265895/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Figs 16A &amp; C</figureCitation>
); sternites light with dark fasciae of varying thickness.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FFF3FFE1FF16F904FDBD89E7" blockId="64.[151,1436,1654,2003]" box="[199,557,1763,1787]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Male Genitalia: Male unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FFF3FFE1FF16F8E0FE69885F" blockId="64.[151,1436,1654,2003]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Intraspecific variation: Maculae on tergite 2 varying slightly in size and shape from ⅓–&lt;½ width of tergite and oval to slightly more triangular.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FFF3FFE1FF16F8A8FB9F8897" blockId="64.[151,1436,1654,2003]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Etymology: This species is named after the systematist Dr. J. Richard Vockeroth, who recognized this as a unique species and labeled the specimens as so, but did not ever describe them.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F8E24FFF3FFE1FF16F870FD6788B3" blockId="64.[151,1436,1654,2003]" box="[199,759,1943,1967]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
Distribution: Southwestern 
<collectingCountry id="F337CEB4FFF3FFE1FE2DF870FDA488B3" box="[508,564,1943,1967]" name="United States of America" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">USA</collectingCountry>
(NM) (
